29:04.366 --> 29:11.453
was growing up was Mexican, Mexican-American.

29:12.093 --> 29:17.778
And these were Mexicans primarily who had come 
over from old Mexico and settled. Because we made a

29:17.798 --> 29:20.901
distinction between, we called them suramacos. 
You're probably familiar with the term. This is

29:23.103 --> 29:26.927
people who came from Mexico to the United States. 
And los manitos, who were Mexicans from New Mexico

29:26.967 --> 29:33.613
or Colorado. who migrated to Rollins. So we made a 
distinction between Mexican-Mexican Americans

29:36.872 --> 29:42.697
and American-Mexican Americans. No, I don't 
think I've heard those terms, but that may be...

29:43.318 --> 29:47.882
Sudomato. S-U-R-U-M-A-T-O.

29:52.085 --> 29:54.607
And this is from a hacienda in Michoacán.

29:57.550 --> 30:00.933
And this is the name they gave themselves to 
indicate their Mexican origin. And Los

30:00.993 --> 30:03.195
Magnitos... There's a publication on Manico 
culture. And these are Spanish people who live in

30:07.068 --> 30:31.731
New Mexico and southern Colorado, who have been in 
the country probably for hundreds of years, and

30:07.068 --> 30:31.731
their descendants, perhaps, of Spanish and 
Indians, or perhaps are of Mexican lineage, but

30:07.068 --> 30:31.731
their forebears came over considerably before 
the Sudamatos, from whom I'm descended. Yeah, but

30:32.234 --> 30:34.277
it was perhaps in the late 19th century. Or early, 
you know, I don't know, you know, maybe the Mexican

30:34.978 --> 30:37.681
War. I just don't know, but I knew, though, that the 
distinction was made when I was growing up. And the

30:42.808 --> 30:52.762
most cutting thing we could say about another 
Mexican was that he was a manito, you see, because

30:42.808 --> 30:52.762
we wanted to indicate that we were really the best 
Mexicans because our parents had just come over

30:42.808 --> 30:52.762
from Mexico. Oh, that's interesting. Yeah, it is. 
You know, we discriminated against ourselves

30:54.124 --> 30:58.630
amongst ourselves as well. You mentioned an 
hacienda in Michoacán as having given sura matos.

31:04.852 --> 31:05.012
Suru. The way I've got it spelled.

31:09.798 --> 31:10.379
It may be this. Yeah, this right here. Now, I got 
this information from a publication by Manuel

31:11.761 --> 31:17.608
Gamil. Are you familiar with some of his works? I 
think that's where I got it. Something I've read,

31:21.092 --> 31:26.999
though, explained the origin of this term, which I 
knew from the time I was very young, but I didn't

31:21.092 --> 31:26.999
know what it was. I just thought, You know, they're 
from Missouri, you know, from South Mexico. This

31:30.611 --> 31:31.112
isn't it. He says that this was from a hacienda. 
This is the name of a hacienda in Michoacán. And

31:35.697 --> 31:53.299
apparently it became

31:35.697 --> 31:53.299
a concept or a symbol to indicate the origin of 
these people in the United States who had come

31:35.697 --> 31:53.299
directly from Mexico rather than being of Mexican 
descent, you know, filtered through several

31:35.697 --> 31:53.299
generations who had lived in the country before 
them. Well, this is interesting because I've

31:53.339 --> 31:56.022
never picked up either one of these terms from East 
Texas or South Texas. There wouldn't be very many

32:01.243 --> 32:05.569
people from New Mexico. There would be Texans who 
were here, Tejanos who were here before the Texas

32:05.609 --> 32:13.160
Revolution, many of them. But I wonder, there may 
be a very real geographical difference here in the

32:13.741 --> 32:19.048
use of terms. Now, again, I wish I had the source at 
my fingertips. I think it's got me, but it may be

32:22.393 --> 32:24.255
somewhere else. But in the literature... There is 
the term, surumato, and they say it's from a

32:25.955 --> 32:30.781
hacienda in Michoacan. Now, this I've got from the 
literature. Someone has got, maybe it's Campa,

32:32.463 --> 32:37.469
Maynard Campa has done something about it. 
Someone, you know, it is in the literature. I was,

32:39.992 --> 32:43.235
well, I've already apologized for not being able 
to read the explanation. Well, what, how many of

32:43.496 --> 32:50.144
the people in your hometown were from Michoacan? I 
don't know. I don't know. I don't know. We had, I

32:56.144 --> 33:12.643
suppose that we didn't have very many friends 
because my uncle's family was a large one and my

32:56.144 --> 33:12.643
mother's family, you know, and I suppose our 
primary friendship, my first memories of any sort

32:56.144 --> 33:12.643
of socialization with cousins, you know. But our 
friends, I suppose, were the Macias, who were also

33:12.663 --> 33:25.358
from Old Mexico,

33:12.663 --> 33:25.358
Los Canos from Old Mexico, I suppose these were the 
closest friends we had. I don't know where they

33:29.791 --> 33:38.984
were from, except that they were from old Mexico 
and maybe from where my parents came from. If you

33:39.946 --> 33:45.153
look at the map, it meets La Barca and Hacona aren't 
too far apart. No, they're not. Isn't Hacona where

33:47.336 --> 33:52.864
Cardenas loves it or Cardenas is from? I don't 
know. I don't know. There was no talk of kindness?

34:00.880 --> 34:02.482
Oh, my father, yes, yes. But no, not in a reasonable 
sense, you know. But kindness, you know, in my

34:06.087 --> 34:16.220
father's hierarchy of values would rank very high 
before I had any formal education at all. You know,

34:16.380 --> 34:19.324
kindness was present in the 34th and 40th, you 
know. I knew about him just as much as I knew about

34:19.743 --> 34:24.327
Abraham Lincoln. These were in my pantheon of 
heroes. And so my father, as I mentioned, was very

34:27.410 --> 34:36.458
prideful of his ancestry and background, and was 
extremely proud of what Cardenas had done. And I'm

34:37.479 --> 34:45.767
quite sure I may be intellectualizing and reading 
into the record something that wasn't there, but

34:37.479 --> 34:45.767
it seems to me that he was very proud of the 
expropriation. And any time the gringos got out,

34:45.787 --> 34:49.530
my father was very happy. And yes, there was 
knowledge, pride, even in Aleman, you know, just

34:50.405 --> 34:58.518
because he's a Mexican president. But not 
regional pride, but he may well have been from

34:59.680 --> 35:03.186
Michoacan. Oh, he was from Michoacan. I wasn't 
sure at the time. Your father kept up with events in

35:09.556 --> 35:12.360
Mexico. Did your mother pay any attention? 
Listen, I've... No, mom was sort of home,

35:16.831 --> 35:21.275
housewife-oriented. My father, my mother, 
again, this is probably post-facto research, has

35:21.295 --> 35:33.907
said that apparently, she said, well, you get your 
ability to speak in public from your father. And

35:34.347 --> 35:40.773
apparently, on Mexican holidays, they would have 
a gathering. My father would give talks, and other

35:40.813 --> 35:44.577
people would give talks. So I have deduced from 
this that he was illiterate in the formal sense,

35:45.046 --> 35:53.559
although he could read and write. But I would 
consider him to be sort of an intellectual in the

35:53.599 --> 36:07.780
sense of trying to place himself in a larger role, 
being aware of public events. Writing poetry, he

36:08.182 --> 36:29.616
wrote poems, love poems to my mother, which is 
something I suppose all of us do, but to have a man of

36:08.182 --> 36:29.616
that background, I think, indicates that he did 
have an interest in education, sympathy, which

36:08.182 --> 36:29.616
probably couldn't be said about a great many of his 
contemporaries. Your father was predominantly

36:31.165 --> 36:34.711
of Spanish background. No, no. My father was very, 
very dark, very Indian. He was very Indian. Was he

36:39.819 --> 36:41.261
Tarascon, perhaps? Or do you know what? I don't 
know. Here's a picture of my mother and my uncle

36:43.364 --> 36:45.668
Tony. You see? Mm-hmm. He's a Haute-A-Tahiti. 
They took off the Tahiti and made it

36:49.314 --> 36:54.582
Haute-A-Tahiti when he was in the United States. 
Wow.

37:01.490 --> 37:03.372
My father was very Indian. If there's someone... 
Now, look, this... Fine, thank you. Now, this is

37:16.625 --> 37:23.231
the only thing I have from my father's...

37:25.413 --> 37:31.159
These clippings and everything in here are his, 
